Our project focuses on evaluating datasets to determine which neighborhood can be considered the “best” based on measurable, 
data-driven criteria. Because “best” is subjective, the first step was identifying which factors most impact quality of life 
and how they can be meaningfully measured. I initially considered several dimensions, including access to recreational spaces, 
public amenities, and overall community resources. However many of these factors overlapd and were difficult to quantify 
consistently across all neighborhoods.

This led me to focus on a more concrete and impactful factor: environmental safety. Specifically, I examined air quality by 
analyzing toxic chemical releases into the air. Air quality directly affects public health, making it a critical and measurable
component of quality of life in the neighborhoods.

The Metric:
The metric I developed focuses on environmental safety, defined by the level of toxic chemical releases into the air within 
each neighborhood. The goal is to assess how exposure to harmful pollutants varies across neighborhoods and how this impacts 
overall living conditions.

Using data from the Western Pennsylvania Regional Data Center (WPRDC), I analyzed total toxic air releases as a key indicator 
of environmental risk. Neighborhoods with lower levels of toxic emissions are considered more favorable, as they suggest 
cleaner air and reduced health risks. This metric is both quantifiable and comparable, allowing for a clear, 
data-driven evaluation of environmental quality across neighborhoods.

Dataset: https://data.wprdc.org/datastore/dump/2750b8c8-246b-430f-b1e0-1aa96e00b013

code:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt


url = "https://data.wprdc.org/datastore/dump/2750b8c8-246b-430f-b1e0-1aa96e00b013"
df = pd.read_csv(url)

df = df[['ZIP_CODE', 'TOTAL_RELEASE']]


df['TOTAL_RELEASE'] = pd.to_numeric(df['TOTAL_RELEASE'], errors='coerce')
df = df.dropna()
df['ZIP_CODE'] = df['ZIP_CODE'].astype(str)


zip_to_neighborhood = {"15206": "East Liberty", "15201": "Lawrenceville", "15213": "Oakland", "15144": "Springdale",
"15104": "Braddock"}
df['neighborhood'] = df['ZIP_CODE'].map(zip_to_neighborhood)


df = df.dropna(subset=['neighborhood'])

grouped = df.groupby('neighborhood')['TOTAL_RELEASE'].sum()
grouped = grouped.sort_values()

print(grouped)
print("\nCleanest neighborhood (lowest total release):", grouped.idxmin())


grouped.plot(kind='bar')
plt.title("Total Toxic Release by Neighborhood")
plt.xlabel("Neighborhood")
plt.ylabel("Total Toxic Release")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

